WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.200
Hi everyone, I'm Javier Luraschi, and today I'm super excited to talk to you about using

00:00:12.200 --> 00:00:18.559
pins with JavaScript and Python. But why? Like, you're probably already aware that

00:00:18.559 --> 00:00:23.639
R is a pretty great programming language for data science, so why should we care?

00:00:23.639 --> 00:00:29.820
Well, let me show you something. There was a survey created by Stack Overflow that shows

00:00:29.820 --> 00:00:36.259
that the top 5 programming languages that are the most popular are JavaScript, HTML

00:00:36.259 --> 00:00:42.020
with CSS, SQL, Python, and Java. These happen to be the programming languages that basically

00:00:42.020 --> 00:00:48.860
run the software in the world. Now, R is not there, it has 5.7% awareness

00:00:48.860 --> 00:00:56.459
compared to 67.7% awareness of JavaScript. So the likelihood of you having to interoperate

00:00:56.459 --> 00:01:01.880
with JavaScript or having to collaborate with someone that loves JavaScript or Python

00:01:01.880 --> 00:01:09.820
or SQL is quite high. So how can we get R to interoperate with these programming languages

00:01:09.820 --> 00:01:14.660
and for us as R data scientists to collaborate with others? And that's what I want to explore

00:01:14.660 --> 00:01:18.860
in this talk. But let me give you some more context. Rather

00:01:18.860 --> 00:01:24.379
than talking about technologies, let's talk about a fictitional team that is working on

00:01:24.379 --> 00:01:29.980
something. And this team is composed by three members. The first one is data scientist Darla.

00:01:29.980 --> 00:01:36.419
Many of you will feel familiar with her because she happens to love R. R is her main programming

00:01:36.419 --> 00:01:41.680
language. She's very into data science and she's very competent with the tools she knows

00:01:41.680 --> 00:01:48.660
and loves, like the tidyverse or tidymodels or even vase R or other packages from the

00:01:48.660 --> 00:01:53.019
R community. There's one more character that we'll introduce,

00:01:53.019 --> 00:01:59.660
which is Graphics Greg. Now, Graphics Greg comes from a background on design and he loves

00:01:59.660 --> 00:02:06.699
using JavaScript. There's no way that Greg is going to learn how to use R. And that's

00:02:06.699 --> 00:02:13.899
not necessarily bad. R is great for data science, but Greg loves doing static websites and helping

00:02:13.899 --> 00:02:18.940
people with their design. So really the skills that he needs are CSS, HTML, and JavaScript,

00:02:18.940 --> 00:02:24.699
and he's very competent with that. And there's one more person that perhaps exemplifies the

00:02:24.699 --> 00:02:30.139
Python community, and this would be machine learning Monica. Monica likes to do machine

00:02:30.139 --> 00:02:34.259
learning with things like network analysis and deep learning, and she happens to love

00:02:34.259 --> 00:02:39.899
Python. She might be familiar with R, but really she's really into Python and it's really hard

00:02:39.899 --> 00:02:46.139
to convince her to do otherwise. So the problem that we have at hand is a pretty

00:02:46.139 --> 00:02:50.259
common problem, which is we live in a world where not everyone speaks the same language.

00:02:50.259 --> 00:02:55.860
Not everyone speaks R. So let's try to solve this problem from the perspective of Darla,

00:02:55.860 --> 00:03:01.539
which is our data scientist who loves R. What can Darla do to get us closer to collaborating

00:03:01.539 --> 00:03:08.460
with Greg and Monica? So a lot of the times what Darla does on her day-to-day is analyzing

00:03:08.460 --> 00:03:12.940
files and she has them in front of her. She has different files, perhaps we can call them

00:03:12.940 --> 00:03:20.820
data frames, and she usually tidies them, analyzes them, shares them, and creates shiny

00:03:20.820 --> 00:03:28.500
applications on R Markdown out of them. And it wouldn't be really acceptable for Darla

00:03:28.500 --> 00:03:34.460
to ask Greg or Monica to have to learn R or to install R and R Studio to really collaborate

00:03:34.460 --> 00:03:39.740
with her. So in her mind, what she's thinking is like, well, if I can share the basic building

00:03:39.740 --> 00:03:45.699
block, which is the dataset that she's working on, if I could share that with Greg and Monica,

00:03:45.699 --> 00:03:51.539
I have a better chance of convincing them of collaborating with me. So what she's going

00:03:51.539 --> 00:03:57.580
on her mind is thinking, well, how can I share these data frames in technologies like GitHub

00:03:57.580 --> 00:04:05.500
or Kaggle or R Studio Connect to kind of like help Greg and Monica reuse my datasets without

00:04:05.500 --> 00:04:11.740
having to install R? And there's actually great news for many of you that are already

00:04:11.740 --> 00:04:17.940
familiar with this particular problem, which is Darla, knowing that she's a competent

00:04:17.940 --> 00:04:23.820
data scientist, knows that there's a package called Pins, which we've been developing in

00:04:23.820 --> 00:04:28.619
the R community for the last year and a half, and allows her to do tasks like this, allows

00:04:28.619 --> 00:04:34.059
her to retrieve data and upload data into the cloud. So what is the Pins package as

00:04:34.059 --> 00:04:39.500
a quick recap? Well, first of all, the Pins package allows you to get a remote resource

00:04:39.500 --> 00:04:44.700
into your local machine. So say if you have like a remote URL with a CSV file, you can

00:04:44.700 --> 00:04:50.059
create a local cache on your machine very easily. Also, once you're connected to those

00:04:50.059 --> 00:04:56.100
remote services like Kaggle or GitHub or R Studio Connect, you can also search those

00:04:56.100 --> 00:05:01.859
services for datasets that are interesting to you, all within the Pins package. And last

00:05:01.859 --> 00:05:06.220
but not least, and especially important for this particular problem that we're trying

00:05:06.220 --> 00:05:11.779
to solve, is the Pins package allows you to share datasets in different cloud providers

00:05:11.779 --> 00:05:18.299
like Google, Kaggle, Azure, and R Studio Connect. And you can do that quite easily. And this

00:05:18.299 --> 00:05:22.980
is something that Darla is already familiar with. She knows that she can share datasets

00:05:22.980 --> 00:05:30.299
with other colleagues that also use R and the Pins package. Now, how does this work?

00:05:30.940 --> 00:05:35.220
The Pins package is actually quite simple. You install it from CRAN, you load the library,

00:05:35.220 --> 00:05:42.220
and then you can ask it to pin a dataset, either an R object or a remote resource or

00:05:42.220 --> 00:05:47.220
a local file into your local board, which is what we're doing in this particular example.

00:05:47.220 --> 00:05:51.500
And then after you pin that resource locally, you can use your favorite tools to process

00:05:51.500 --> 00:05:56.619
it. Like in this case, we're just reading a remote JSON file, saving it locally, and

00:05:56.619 --> 00:06:01.179
then using JSON Lite to read it. Now, that's the simple use case of the Pins package to

00:06:01.179 --> 00:06:05.660
bring things into your local machine. But you can also use the Pins package to push

00:06:05.660 --> 00:06:12.579
things out of your local machine. And what Darla could do here potentially is register

00:06:12.579 --> 00:06:17.700
a board, which is a concept from the Pins package. The board that she registers could

00:06:17.700 --> 00:06:27.459
be GitHub, DigitalOcean, Google Cloud, RStudio, Kaggle, Azure, or AWS S3. And she can basically

00:06:27.459 --> 00:06:33.859
push the dataset from something as simple of an array of 10 numbers by saying, pin one

00:06:33.859 --> 00:06:40.500
to 10, name equals numbers, and then board equals, say, Google Cloud, whatever.

00:06:40.500 --> 00:06:47.260
And the dataset that she has locally can be pushed to be shared to those particular services.

00:06:47.260 --> 00:06:50.779
And if she needs to get it back at any point in time, she can just say, pin get, and the

00:06:50.779 --> 00:06:55.899
dataset will come back from those services into her local machine again.

00:06:55.899 --> 00:07:01.059
You can do a little bit more complex stuff. Like you can say, suppose that you're collaborating

00:07:01.059 --> 00:07:06.100
in an image processing project and you have ImageNet, you can retrieve a smaller version

00:07:06.100 --> 00:07:11.739
of ImageNet called TinyImageNet by saying, pin this remote resource locally into my local

00:07:11.739 --> 00:07:17.380
machine and we'll call it ImageNet. And then what you can do is you can also say, oh, give

00:07:17.380 --> 00:07:23.260
me back ImageNet, and now I want to push it to perhaps Kaggle, because maybe you did some

00:07:23.260 --> 00:07:27.820
cleaning of the data or some processing. So all of these are tasks that the Pins package

00:07:27.820 --> 00:07:34.339
supports, including finding. You can just say, pin find, and it will find the different

00:07:34.339 --> 00:07:37.540
datasets that are available in the different boards.

00:07:37.540 --> 00:07:43.059
So this is quite great. And if we think about it from Darla's point of view, we're pretty

00:07:43.059 --> 00:07:49.339
close to the space that Greg and Monica are interested. We've moved our datasets from

00:07:49.339 --> 00:07:55.739
our local machine to the cloud. But then again, we have the question that in this case, Nelson

00:07:55.739 --> 00:08:01.859
Bigetti is asking and he's thinking, wait, this is a pretty great package for the R community.

00:08:01.859 --> 00:08:06.820
Why can't we just do the same from JavaScript or Python? Rather than having to be downloading

00:08:06.820 --> 00:08:12.220
random JSON files or CSV files and figuring out authentication and permissions, why can't

00:08:12.220 --> 00:08:17.779
we just have the same code being used in Python or JavaScript? And sure enough, the whole

00:08:17.779 --> 00:08:24.260
point of this talk is for me to introduce you to a new project, PinsJS, which is a reimplementation

00:08:24.260 --> 00:08:30.019
of the PinsR package into JavaScript that supports Python as well. This enables you

00:08:30.019 --> 00:08:39.059
to use pins from technologies like web browser with HTML or web applications running Node.js

00:08:39.059 --> 00:08:45.380
or even Python. And the way that we accomplish this is basically by reimplementing the functionality

00:08:45.380 --> 00:08:51.500
available on R in JavaScript. And this allows you to interoperate with R. So if someone

00:08:51.500 --> 00:08:56.539
shares a dataset from R, you can then quite easily get the dataset from JavaScript or

00:08:56.539 --> 00:09:02.859
Python, which is quite great, and even push datasets from Python and JavaScript back into

00:09:02.859 --> 00:09:09.099
cloud service providers. So how does this look like? Well, here we have some HTML code.

00:09:09.099 --> 00:09:16.280
It's quite simple. It's declaring that this particular HTML file needs the pins library

00:09:16.280 --> 00:09:21.719
and also is running within the browser environment. And then we're basically just defining some

00:09:21.719 --> 00:09:27.400
JavaScript callbacks to use pins. In this particular case, we are saying board register

00:09:27.400 --> 00:09:32.359
to register a local board. And then we're creating a dataset, which the dataset is just

00:09:32.359 --> 00:09:37.299
the number 42, and we're saving it in a local board. And then we're retrieving the value

00:09:37.299 --> 00:09:47.520
and then we're printing it into the web page inside a div, which is our result. And we

00:09:47.520 --> 00:09:51.200
can complicate this a little bit more. Rather than just creating one dataset, we can create

00:09:51.200 --> 00:09:56.679
multiple datasets in JavaScript, say using a for loop from one to 10, we'll push those

00:09:56.679 --> 00:10:02.219
datasets into the local board. And then we can search them and create perhaps a page

00:10:02.219 --> 00:10:07.260
table on JavaScript that shows us all the different pins that we have stored, which

00:10:07.260 --> 00:10:14.239
you can see on the top right. And we can even go a little bit step further.

00:10:14.239 --> 00:10:19.520
If you're really into state-of-the-art JavaScript applications, you can use a library called

00:10:19.520 --> 00:10:26.239
Babel, which allows you to transpile modern JavaScript into compatible JavaScript. And

00:10:26.239 --> 00:10:33.919
you can make use of perhaps the new pipe operator to get the iris JSON file using pins and then

00:10:33.919 --> 00:10:41.719
pipe it into the function that basically reads this dataset from JSON, and then creating

00:10:41.719 --> 00:10:45.840
a data table with the entire iris dataset. And that's what we see on the top right.

00:10:45.840 --> 00:10:51.159
So again, you're just using JavaScript to different degrees, using pins in the way that

00:10:51.159 --> 00:10:57.799
you would expect to use JavaScript. And similar for Python, if you want to use pins from Python,

00:10:57.799 --> 00:11:06.960
all you have to do is run pip install with a URL that is hosting the pins.js Python library.

00:11:06.960 --> 00:11:11.719
And then you import the library with import pins, and then you create pins with pins pin

00:11:11.719 --> 00:11:17.159
number 42, and then the board where you're storing this data into. You can also do things

00:11:17.159 --> 00:11:21.799
like retrieving a pin, obviously, from either the local board or a remote board. And then

00:11:21.799 --> 00:11:26.200
you can also find and to figure out which are the pins that are available to you, which

00:11:26.200 --> 00:11:30.280
in this case is just the number that we just pinned on the iris dataset.

00:11:30.280 --> 00:11:36.200
All right. So this gives us kind of like a pretty broad overview of how the pins package

00:11:36.200 --> 00:11:41.039
works. But we want to see it in action on a real kind of like use case. So let's think

00:11:41.359 --> 00:11:46.679
about this. Darla, Greg, and Monica get together over a lunch, and they're trying to figure

00:11:46.679 --> 00:11:52.719
out which is the most important character of the last book in Game of Thrones. So, you

00:11:52.719 --> 00:11:59.280
know, like they have some insight that perhaps, you know, like either Daenerys or maybe Tyrion

00:11:59.280 --> 00:12:03.320
are the most important characters, but they can't really figure out exactly which one

00:12:03.320 --> 00:12:08.039
is the most important one. So Darla, being the competent data scientist that we know

00:12:08.200 --> 00:12:13.520
she is, she just after lunch, she gets back to her office and, you know, launches the

00:12:13.520 --> 00:12:22.760
R instance and runs the pins library to find out if there's any interesting datasets on

00:12:22.760 --> 00:12:28.799
the Kaggle service. And sure enough, she finds that Kaggle has at least three datasets, one

00:12:28.799 --> 00:12:33.679
containing all the scripts from the HBO series, the other one, the subtitles, and the third

